column249: I assumed the other player was only looking out for himself  so I maximized my profits based on that assumption. A few times  when it was unclear what the other player would choose (they might choose to play even if it were a risk)  I tried to collaborate so that we would earn more together  but the other player usually defected. Otherwise  I always tried to pick the option that gave me more money even if it meant the other player would lose  because I assumed the other player would do the same. If the game was pretty random  then we should both make some money.

If I knew the state for sure and it was greater than the sure payoff  I played. When I knew it was one of two for sure  I considered if the other player knew it was one for sure or one of two for sure. If that didn't tell me the best move  I checked if the expected value of my choices was greater than the sure payoff or not.
in certain cases I could assume what the other player might do so I knew that my choice wouldn't really matter...not thinking is nice.

If guaranteed to know which state  if state is more than sure payoff  say 'yes.' Otherwise  say 'no.' |  | If unsure between two states  see other player. If other player's isolated slot is less than sure payoff  and that isolated state is one in which I'd make less money  and the other state is one in which I'd make more money  say yes. |  | Otherwise  say no.
Consider the positions of both players

I first determined whether I knew the state. If yes  I compared the states payout to the sure payoff. If the state payoff was more I clicked play if it was less I clicked don't play. If I did not know the pay off  I then compared my row the my partners. If (s)he would want to play only when I would want to play I clicked play. If (s)he would want to play only when I would not want to play  I clicked don't play. If we would both want to play probabilistically then I compared my expected earnings to the sure payoff. I then clicked play if and only if my expected earnings were greater than the sure payoff.  |  | A few rounds I forgot to check all of my opponents possibilities so I did not play optimally.

If I am certain of the game state  then I only need to compare my payoff versus the sure payoff. |      If I am uncertain  first I check my payoffs  the payoff of the opposing players if he/she is sure of the outcome  and the sure payoff. If his payoff when he is sure of the outcome is less the the sure payoff  I know he will answer no in that case  and there is no possibility I will receive the payoff I would receive in that state. Then I can compare the payoff I have in the other state (B in this case)  and see if it is greater than the sure case. If his payoff when he is sure of the state is greater than the "sure payoff"  I average the two possible values  and play if that average is greater than the "sure payoff".

If I knew the state for sure  I would just compare the numberi n that state with the for sure payoff and play accordingly. If I didn't know the exact state  I would first look at the other players numbers. If their exact known state payoff was lower than the for sure payoff  I would click anything. If their payoff was higher than the for sure payoff  I would look at my possible payoffs and weigh amount possibly lost to amount possibly won. When considering the case where we both don't know for sure  I would again wiegh amount possibly won to amount possibly lost.

Basic strategy: only play the game if your expected value for doing so is greater than the sure payoff.  |  | Refinement: Also take into account your opponent's actions. For example  say you know the state is either A or B  and your payoff for A is below the sure payoff while your payoff for B is above. If player 2's payoff for A is also below the sure payoff  you can assume that if player 2 knows the state to be A  he will vote "no". Thus  if you vote "yes"  you cannot get below the value of the sure payoff  because player 2 could only vote "yes" if your true payoff is above the sure payoff.

If I had definite knowledge that it was a bad or good deal for me  I decided to not play or play the game accordingly  of course. |  | If the payoffs were identical for Players 1 and 2  and I did not have knowledge that it was definitely a bad deal for me  I played the game.  |  | Otherwise  I imagined the other player using my same strategy and tried to deduce how they would play in each possible situation. When it was in their interest to give me a bad deal  I decided not to play.

Start with the single values  eliminate the values that the other player would choose 'No' on. Then make choice depends on the value left for me. If it's greater than Sure payoff  then choose 'Yes'. Vice versa.

Predict whether the other player would play the game or not based on different possible states.  If the other player would play regardless of the possible state  take the expected value of the two possible payoffs.  If this is greater than the sure payoff  play anyway.  If less  do not play.  If the other player will play given one state  but will not play given another  play if the payoff for the state in which the other player would play is greater than the sure payoff.  Otherwise  do not play.
